The consensus of almost three dozen
    investment analysts is for a continuing bull market in stocks, with returns of eight to 10
    percent. Mutual fund analyst Kirk Kazanjian conducted the survey of market gurus,
    which included Elaine Garzarelli, technology guru Michael Murphy, newsletter
    editor Al Frank, and Forbes columnist David Dreman. "Overall, these
    experts still believe the stock market is the place to be," Kazanjian says.
    "They just don't expect the incredible ride we've been on for the past few years to
    continue. In essence, they're looking for a breather that could last into the new
    millennium." Kazanjian includes the analysts' thoughts in a new book, Wall Street's
    Picks for 1998. Previous editions have included valuable information. "In 1996, my
    investment panel accurately called for a strong bull market, even though the overall
    sentiment at the time was bearish," he notes. "Then in 1997, these advisors
    warned of a correction that would shave stock prices between 10 and 20 percent during the
    year, which was right again."

Headlines.Author: CBS.MarketWatch.com
Headlines.Headline: Yahoo beats numbers

#text: Shares of Yahoo!

may get a boost Thursday after the Internet search engine said revenue for its fourth
    quarter nearly tripled from last year, pushing earnings ahead of analysts' expectations.
    The Santa Clara, Calif.-based company said it earned 5 cents per share, 2 cents ahead of
    Wall Street projections. Revenue increased 181 percent to $25.1 million, about $5 million
    ahead of the expectations of BancAmerica Robertson Stephens analyst Keith Benjamin. Daily
    page views soared to 65 million. That is more than analysts expected and is up from 50
    million in the previous quarter. Yahoo! rivals Excite
and Infoseek

are scheduled to report next Thursday, and Benjamin predicts they will both beat published
    expectations. Ahead of the release, Yahoo! rose 1 7/32 to 67.

Headlines.Author: Binti T. Harvey
Headlines.Headline: Apple beats Street

#text:
Shares of Apple
    Computer Inc.

may move higher Thursday following the computer maker's report of
    better-than-expected first-quarter earnings. Apple earned 37 cents a share, compared to a
    loss of 96 cents a share a year ago. The consensus estimate of analysts surveyed by First
    Call was 35 cents a share, revised upward after interim CEO Steve Jobs surprised the
    Street last week by saying Apple would report its first profit in over a year.
    First-quarter revenue decreased to $1.6 billion from $2.1 billion a year ago. Gross
    margins rose to 22 percent from 19 percent a year ago. The company attributed its gain to
    the launch of its Power Macintosh G3 computers, which shipped 133,000 units in the
    quarter. The company said returning Apple to "sustainable profitability" will be
    its number one objective in fiscal 1998. Shares closed up 1/4 at 19 3/4 ahead of the
    report. See
    release.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Apple beats Street
